## UI Framework — vinext

Use **vinext** for all new web UI and full-stack projects. It is a drop-in replacement for Next.js, reimplemented on Vite, with one-command Cloudflare Workers deployment.

```bash
# Add to an existing project
bun add vinext

# Migrate an existing Next.js project (automated)
bun x vinext init

# Development server (replaces next dev)
vinext dev

# Production build (replaces next build)
vinext build

# Deploy to Cloudflare Workers
vinext deploy

# Preview production build locally
vinext start
```

Existing `app/`, `pages/`, and `next.config.js` files work as-is — no code changes required.

### package.json scripts

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev":    "vinext dev",
    "build":  "vinext build",
    "start":  "vinext start",
    "deploy": "vinext deploy"
  }
}
```

### justfile

Standard targets: `install` (`bun install`), `dev` (`vinext dev`), `build` (`vinext build`), `deploy` (`vinext deploy`), `test` (`bun test`), `ci` (`just typecheck lint test build`). See `task-runner.mdc` for the full justfile pattern.

### Migration from Next.js

| Next.js | vinext |
|---|---|
| `next dev` | `vinext dev` |
| `next build` | `vinext build` |
| `next start` | `vinext start` |
| `next export` | `vinext deploy` |
| `npm install next` | `bun add vinext` |

All App Router, Pages Router, React Server Components, Server Actions, and middleware work identically.

> **Note**: vinext is experimental. Check [github.com/cloudflare/vinext](https://github.com/cloudflare/vinext) for known limitations before using advanced Next.js features.
